{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Mpu7DTSA6aPNzmxQW2ip4D","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue. The `read_search_in_tx` function creates a transaction and calls `tx.prepare(...)` for:\n1. `vec0_match` - \"SELECT rowid FROM vector_default WHERE embedding MATCH vec_f32(?1) ORDER BY distance LIMIT 10\"\n2. `canonical_lookup` - \"SELECT body FROM canonical_nodes WHERE write_cursor = ?1 LIMIT 1\"\n3. `soft_fallback_probe` - the `query_row` with \"SELECT 1 FROM search_index JOIN ...\" \n4. `fts_match` - \"SELECT body FROM search_index WHERE search_index MATCH ?1 ORDER BY write_cursor\"\n\n\nThe real problem is that `prepare_cached` lives on the `Connection`, not the `Transaction`, so calling `tx.prepare(...)` creates uncached temporary statements. Since `Transaction` dereferences to the underlying `Connection`, I can use `tx.prepare_cached(...)` instead, and the statement cache will persist across transaction boundaries. or rolls back, the cached statements remain valid. So I should switch all four `prepare` calls to `prepare_cached`. But looking more closely at the code, the `soft_fallback_probe` statement is actually used inside a `query_row` call rather than being prepared explicitly, which means it's handled differently than the other three statements. Let me check whether `query_row` even uses the statement cache under the hood.\n\nLooking at the rusqlite source, `query_row` calls `prepare` directly instead of `prepare_cached`, so I'd need to either find a `query_row_cached` method if it exists in the version being used, or convert that call to an explicit `prepare_cached` followed by the query. Let me check the Cargo.toml to see which rusqlite version is in use, since the cached query methods might only be available in newer versions.\n\nNow tracing through the actual prepare calls in the code: the vec0_match, canonical_lookup, and soft_fallback_probe calls are all conditional based on whether query_vector exists, and the fts_match prepare happens separately. The diagnostic showing 4 prepares per search suggests these conditions are all being hit in the test case, so I need to verify which ones are actually executing together. I'm looking at the A.3 measurements more carefully—the metrics show 1600 total queries with 542 microseconds per query, which suggests the 4 prepares were actually measured from that test run. The key insight is that `query_row` internally creates its own prepared statement, so when I trace through all the prepare calls across `load_projection_cursor`, `vec0_match`, `canonical_lookup`, `soft_fallback_probe`, and `fts_match`, I'm likely counting more than 4 statements total.\n\nLet me examine what `load_projection_cursor` is doing internally.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2621,"cache_read_input_tokens":33242,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2621},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"de830eed-a5da-41aa-8176-21ca57079190"}
