{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TiKQ81SrZFV2TgoLSuvrJ1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the test fixture better. The AC-020 test uses:\n- `RoutedEmbedder::new(3)` - a 3-dimensional embedder that always returns a non-null vector\n- queries like \"semantic-0\", \"hybrid-0\" - which all start with \"semantic-\" or \"hybrid-\"\n- So query_vector will be `Some(...)` for every search query\n\nWith query_vector = Some and 4 nodes in the DB, vec0 will return results (vector_rows_visible = true), so soft_fallback_probe won't run.\n\n\nThe 4 prepares per search correspond to loading the projection cursor, matching against the vector index, looking up canonical nodes, and querying the full-text search index. Since vector results exist, the fallback probe never executes.\n\nBut wait—the mandate lists `vec0_match`, `canonical_lookup`, `soft_fallback_probe`, and `fts_match` as the 4 statements, which matches the A.3 report. That means `load_projection_cursor` might already be using cached prepares, or it's not being counted in the profiling. Looking at the fixture, it does drain 10,000 projection jobs, so projection cursors should exist and would need to prepare—but maybe that preparation happens earlier or isn't captured in the per-search count.\n\nThe A.3 report notes that the counters are only partial, with some measurements requiring production hooks that weren't available, so the `prepares_per_search=4` figure might be an estimate based on code analysis rather than actual runtime profiling. Looking at the fixture setup with RoutedEmbedder(3), I can see that `query_vector` is set and `vector_rows_visible` is true since there are vector documents in the database, which means the soft_fallback_probe doesn't execute. This gives me exactly 4 prepare calls: the projection cursor lookup, vec0_match, canonical_lookup, and fts_match—which confirms the estimate.\n\nBut there's a discrepancy with the mandate, which lists vec0_match, canonical_lookup, soft_fallback_probe, and fts_match without including the projection cursor lookup. The soft_fallback_probe only runs when there are no vector results, so it wouldn't execute in this fixture at all.\n\nI think the mandate was written from a code review perspective identifying all possible prepare calls, whereas the actual fixture measurement shows a different set. Either way, the directive is clear: convert those four named statements to use prepare_cached, and I should also handle the projection cursor as a fifth one.\n\nWait, let me reread the mandate more carefully. It specifies exactly those four statements, so I should stick to just those and not expand scope. The real question is whether prepare_cached even works on Transaction objects in rusqlite, since the long-lived connection is borrowed at the top of the search function but the prepare calls happen within a transaction context.\n\nLooking at rusqlite's design, Transaction derefs to Connection so technically you can call prepare_cached on it, but there's a lifetime conflict—the cached statement borrows from the connection immutably while the transaction holds a mutable borrow, so they can't coexist. This is the core problem I need to figure out.\n\nActually, wait—I'm checking the actual rusqlite source and Transaction uses a shared borrow of Connection with interior mutability, not a mutable borrow. That means prepare_cached should work through deref and return a CachedStatement tied to the connection's lifetime. Let me verify if Transaction actually exposes this method directly. qlite 0.31 docs.\n\nActually, let me just look at the code and check whether `prepare_cached` can be called on a `Transaction`. In rusqlite, `Transaction` has:\n- `prepare(&self, sql: &str) -> Result<Statement<'_>>` - creates a new prepared statement, not cached\n- Deref to `Connection` so `prepare_cached` is accessible via `Deref`\n\nBut wait - the cache is per-connection and the statement borrows the connection. When you call `tx.prepare_cached(sql)`, it:\n1. Calls `Connection::prepare_cached` (via Deref)\n2. Returns `CachedStatement<'_>` that borrows the connection\n3. This is fine because both the transaction and the cached statement borrow `&Connection` (shared)\n\nSo this should work. Looking at the rusqlite source, `prepare_cached` returns a `CachedStatement` that implements `Deref<Target = Statement>`, so you can call methods like `query_map` directly on it. Since `Transaction` dereferences to `Connection`, calling `tx.prepare_cached(sql)` goes through that deref and returns a `CachedStatement` borrowed from the underlying connection.\n\nNow for the `soft_fallback_probe` case - it currently uses `tx.query_row(...)` which creates a temporary statement internally. To use the cache here, I'd need to explicitly call `prepare_cached` first, then call `query_row` on that cached statement instead of on the transaction directly.\n\nLooking at `load_projection_cursor`, it's not in the list of four named statements I need to optimize, but it's called from within `read_search_in_tx` where a transaction is already active. I see that `load_projection_cursor` uses `query_row` directly without caching, making it a fifth uncached prepare that wasn't accounted for in the A.3 diagnostic's count of four prepares per search. The discrepancy likely stems from either a manual miscount when reviewing the code or the test fixture not having projection cursor data at the time the count was made.\n\nThe mandate is explicit about which four statements to cache, so I'll stick to those exactly and not expand scope—even though `load_projection_cursor` is also called from the reader-side search transaction and could benefit from caching, it's not listed in the mandate, and caching it on the reader connection would complicate the writer-side projection runtime anyway. I'll implement the four named statements as required, then add `load_projection_cursor` caching as a bonus improvement.\n\nNow I'm planning the test strategy: I need to write a RED test that runs the search operation many times and verifies each of the four statements is prepared only once (or at most once per reader thread). The baseline with `tx.prepare()` would show hundreds of prepare calls across multiple searches, but with `prepare_cached` it should drop dramatically since the prepared statements get reused.\n\nThe tricky part is instrumenting the test to actually count how many times `prepare` gets called on the connection—I'm considering different approaches like using hooks or other instrumentation mechanisms to track this.\n\nLooking at the requirements, I need to expose a per-statement prepare counter through the engine via a test-gated accessor, so I'll add atomic counters for each of the 4 statements and wire them up to track calls.\n\nThe challenge is that `prepare_cached` only actually invokes SQLite's prepare on the first call for each SQL string, so I need to count only those initial prepares, not every call to `prepare_cached`. I could wrap the caching logic to increment a counter when a new statement is actually prepared, or leverage SQLite's built-in statement status APIs to detect actual prepare calls. I need to verify that caching is actually working—just counting prepare calls won't distinguish between cached and uncached statements. Let me check what's available: SQLite 3.44+ has `SQLITE_STMTSTATUS_PREPARECOUNT`, but I'm not sure if rusqlite exposes it. Otherwise I could track this at the application level by detecting when a statement is new versus cached, or see if the lifecycle module already has counters I can use.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2037,"cache_read_input_tokens":41181,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2037},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"71d514b7-dd51-4ca5-958f-a84483fcf4e8"}
