{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SGow9YUn2P6gBSUpXd3MN3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture:\n\n1. `StatementStatus::Run` (value 6) = `SQLITE_STMTSTATUS_RUN` - how many times the statement has been run. This is the metric I can use!\n\n2. rusqlite's `prepare_cached` implementation: \n   - Looks up SQL in the LRU cache\n   - Cache HIT: returns an existing `Statement` (a cached one that was previously used, so `get_status(Run) > 0`)\n   - Cache MISS: calls `conn.prepare_with_flags(...)` → newly prepared statement, `get_status(Run) == 0`\n   \nSo I can detect cache hits by checking if `stmt.get_status(StatementStatus::Run)` is greater than 0 after `prepare_cached` — a zero means it's freshly prepared, while any positive value indicates it's a reused statement from the cache with accumulated execution history.\n\nNow I'm laying out the implementation: I'll add an atomic counter to the Engine struct, modify the search function to accept this counter, and after each prepare call check if the Run status is zero to detect misses. Then I'll expose test methods to read and reset this counter, and write a test that exercises the fixture and verifies the prepare miss count.\n\nFor the RED phase before the fix, I need to count every prepare call the same way—by checking if the statement's Run status is zero, which works for both `tx.prepare()` and the cached version since both Statement types expose `get_status()`.\n\nFor the GREEN phase with caching, the counter only increments on cache misses when Run equals zero, so across 100 searches using the same SQL, I'd see just a handful of increments rather than hundreds.\n\nI'm now checking whether the Run count persists or resets when a CachedStatement is dropped... to `prepare_cached`, I need to refactor the soft_fallback_probe to use a cached prepared statement instead of creating a new one each time. The `query_row` method takes a mutable reference, so I can call it on the cached statement without consuming it. However, this optimization only matters when the soft fallback probe actually runs—which requires both vector results and the condition where they're not visible, and in my current test setup that path isn't even being triggered. I see the issue now—`load_projection_cursor` is making an additional prepared statement call that I'm not converting to `prepare_cached`, so even though only 3 of the 4 statements I'm targeting actually run in the test fixture, there's still a 4th statement being prepared elsewhere that's inflating the count. That's why the baseline is hitting 400 prepares instead of the expected 300.\n\nThe solution is to exclude `load_projection_cursor` from the counter entirely and only track the 4 named statements I'm actually optimizing: `vec0_match`, `canonical_lookup`, `soft_fallback_probe`, and `fts_match`. With that scope, the baseline becomes 100 × 3 = 300 prepares.\n\nWait, I'm getting confused about which statements actually run in the fixture. The diagnostic showed 4 prepares per search, but that includes `load_projection_cursor` which I'm not counting. And `soft_fallback_probe` doesn't execute in this test scenario at all. So I need to clarify exactly which 3 statements are running and being counted against the 32-prepare limit. I see the discrepancy now—the mandate expects 400 baseline prepares (all 4 named statements uncached across 100 searches), but my counter only tracks 3 of them, giving 300. I need to clarify whether the fourth statement should be included in the count or if the baseline expectation needs adjustment.\n\nLet me check if `soft_fallback_probe` can also use the cached prepare approach, which would bring it into the counter and align with the expected numbers.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the full solution: adding a `search_prepare_misses` counter to the Engine struct, initializing it in the engine open path, modifying `read_search_in_tx` to accept and increment the counter on cache misses, and threading it through from `search_inner`.\n\nI'll also need to switch the four `prepare` calls to `prepare_cached` with cache-miss detection logic after each one, and add a comment explaining the invariant on the first call.\n\nFor the test file, I'll write the RED test first to verify the cache-miss detection is working before implementing the actual fix.\n\nLet me start by locating where the Engine struct is initialized to add the new field.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1709,"cache_read_input_tokens":70641,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1709},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"36694b1e-3ff1-422e-a859-8ac9163d01f4"}
