{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VwU96jR13Jp3v6jp7xQn3Y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me implement the changes step by step.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n1. Add `StatementStatus` to rusqlite imports\n2. Add `search_prepare_misses: AtomicU64` to Engine struct\n3. Initialize in open path\n4. Add test accessor methods to Engine\n5. Change `read_search_in_tx` signature and implementation (RED state first - with `tx.prepare()`, adding counter increments)\n6. Update `search_inner` to pass the counter\n7. Write the RED test file\n8. Run to confirm RED\n\n\n9. Switch to `prepare_cached` with cache-miss detection\n10. Run to confirm GREEN\n11. Run full test suite\n\nI need to follow the mandate properly—since I'm in a worktree starting from the `0.6.0-rewrite` tip, I should add the counter infrastructure and test first, run it to confirm RED, then switch to `prepare_cached` and verify GREEN. Let me start by making all the Engine changes in lib.rs in phases.\n\nFor the `soft_fallback_probe` counter, I'll skip it in the RED phase since it doesn't run in the AC-020 fixture and would require instrumenting `query_row`. I'll add counters for `vec0_match`, `canonical_lookup`, and `fts_match` first (the `tx.prepare()` calls), then add `soft_fallback_probe` later when I switch to `prepare_cached`.\n\nNow I'm deciding whether `prepare_miss_counter` should be always-present or debug-only—looking at how `force_next_commit_failure` uses `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`, I should probably follow that pattern.\n\nActually, `provenance_row_cap` is always-present with a test-only accessor, which is cleaner than spreading cfg conditionals everywhere. I'll use that same approach: add the field as always-present, initialize it to zero, and provide a test accessor method.\n\nAdding the struct field and initialization...\n\nWriting the accessor methods...\n\nNow I need to thread the counter through `search_inner` into `read_search_in_tx` so it can be incremented during the RED phase. Writing the query execution logic... Writing database query logic... I'm realizing there's a lifetime issue here—when `prepare_cached` is called on `Transaction` via `Deref`, the returned `CachedStatement` gets a lifetime tied to the deref operation itself, not the original `'conn` lifetime of the transaction, which could cause problems with how long the statement is actually valid. I see that `prepare_cached` returns a `CachedStatement` with a lifetime tied to the borrow of `self`, so when called on a `Transaction` via `Deref`, the lifetime would be bound to how long the transaction borrow is active. That should work fine for my use case since I'm using the statement within the same scope. Let me check if there are actual examples of calling `prepare_cached` on transactions in the rusqlite codebase or in the existing fathomdb code to confirm this pattern is supported.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2392,"cache_read_input_tokens":77813,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2392},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"771379b6-bcaf-4f59-a9a6-889bec008755"}
