{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012VZ2jTw471gLz5VcE5SfyH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `prepare_cached_readers_miss_count_saturates` test is failing because:\n- 1000-iter misses = 3 (the cache warms up on first use, so after 1000 iterations there are only 3 cache misses total)\n- 10-iter warm-up misses = 0 (but wait... why is this 0?)\n\nWait, 1000-iter misses = 3, but 10-iter warm-up misses = 0? That's because:\n- 1000 searches = 3 misses in total (one per unique SQL at first use)\n\n\n- After resetting the counter, 10 more searches = 0 new misses (cache is already warm from the previous 1000)\n\nSo the test assertion `misses_1000 <= misses_warmup + 2` becomes `3 <= 0 + 2` = `3 <= 2` which fails. The real issue is that the test's logic is flawed—it's trying to verify the cache doesn't grow indefinitely, but the cache is already hot from the initial 1000 runs, so the reset counter shows 0 misses, which is actually correct behavior.\n\nI think the better approach is to restructure the test: warm up with 10 searches to capture initial misses, reset the counter, then run 990 more searches and verify those show 0 misses since the cache is fully primed. Or I could just simplify it—the 1000-search test already shows 3 misses, which is well within acceptable bounds, so the saturation test might be redundant. Let me either remove it or fix the assertion logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":623,"cache_read_input_tokens":97058,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":623},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"fdc47c5f-8d48-4b0f-aece-2982ef53bf92"}
